POLICE/MUNICIPAL COURTS - Aid. Clauss, Chairman (Cruts, Harrell, Jokerst)
Consideration of a request by STL Athletic Center to amend the Traffic Code to allow parking on Hitzert Court.
Michael Marscheutz of STL Athletic Center, located at 2300 Hitzert Court, is requesting an amendment to the Code to allow parking along Hitzert Court, which is not permitted at any time under Schedule VIII of the City's Traffic Code.

STL Athletic Center received approval of a Special Use Permit (SUP) to operate an Indoor Unlimited Recreational Facility under Ordinance 3907, as amended by Ordinance 4213, with a condition that, "the parking on-site shall be/remain sufficient for the use of the property." Recently, large events (gun shows, sneaker events) have been held at this location where on-site parking has not been sufficient for the use, putting their SUP at risk of being revoked.

Mike Marscheutz, 2300 Hitzert Court, Fenton MO 63026 shared a presentation overview outlining his request for additional parking (attached as part of the minutes). He is proposing parallel parking spaces on the shoulder of Hitzert Court on both sides of his building, of which Hitzert Court is owned by STL Athletic. Additional parking would only be utilized for big events (4-6 per year) when there are slow times of his business. Currently, he is using the neighboring business parking lot with verbal authorization of the tenant, which is not allowed under the City Code. STL Athletic proposes to pave and stripe the gravel shoulder in the next year if the proposal is approved.

Mr. Marscheutz shared Hitzert Court is very wide to help facilitate truck traffic, approximately forty feet (40') wide in some areas not including the shoulder. He feels he could maintain parallel parking with a pedestrian walkway.

Mayor Maurath inquired if more parking spaces could be created on the back side of the building and if the City has ability to regulate private street parking. City Attorney Erin Seele replied yes for safety reasons.

City Administrator Nikki Finkbiner noted there could be concerns with swales in Metropolitan Sewer District (MSD) right-of-way due to additional impervious surfaces. She further shared a typical street is twenty-six feet (26') wide within a fifty-foot (50') right-of-way. City Administrator Nikki Finkbiner shared the Fenton Fire Protection District (FFPD) stated they do not have concerns of parking along the eastern part of Hitzert Court with the width of the road. City Administrator Nikki Finkbiner expressed concerns that if striped it may be deemed a parking lot not an access way placing it under a different Code. She suggested it not be striped and deemed on street parking.

City Administrator Nikki Finkbiner has discussed with Mr. Marscheutz that he needs to review the existing access easement agreements on the property, minimally with the property to the north (lot B), to determine if this parking may cause any violations of same.

Alderman Clauss inquired on concerns of parked cars being hit by trucks entering and exiting docking facilities located across the street. Mr. Marscheutz expressed he does not believe there are any concerns as there is no through traffic and events occur on the weekends when that business is not open. Alderman Clauss inquired how many additional parking spaces are being proposed, Mr. Marscheutz replied sixty-five (65) additional parallel parking spaces, fifteen (15) along the north portion and fifty (50) along the east portion.

Alderman Maserang shared he perceives it as a shoulder improvement and is not opposed to the request and further inquired why it is not allowed to utilize adjacent business parking. City Administrator Nikki Finkbiner replied shared parking is allowed under the Code with a written agreement from the property owner.

Alderman Bereitschaft shared he is in favor of additional parking and suggested utilizing temporary signs for parking during events.

City Administrator Nikki Finkbiner voiced after further review of the graveled shoulder; she would deem the request a shoulder improvement without concerns of swales being affected.

Sergeant Begley shared that he inspected the property and that he did not see concern for street parking along the eastern portion of Hitzert Court but does have concern on the back northern portion of Hitzert as it is not wide enough to allow for street parking unless that portion of Hitzert Court is widened.

Mayor Maurath inquired if approved and becomes an issue in future if the no parking prohibition could be reinstated. City Attorney Erin Seele replied yes, as it is a police power not zoning.

Following discussion, Alderman Clauss made a motion to forward to the June Board of Aldermen meeting the consideration of a request by STL Athletic Center to amend the Traffic Code to only allow on-street parking on the front eastern portion of Hitzert Court. The motion was seconded by Alderman Cruts. Upon a vote being taken, it was announced that the motion was unanimously passed by the Committee.

